{"id":"2004.09953","submitter":"Basudeb Datta Prof.","authors":"Basudeb Datta","title":"Vertex-transitive covers of semi-equivelar toroidal maps","comments":"7 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A map $X$ on a surface is called vertex-transitive if the automorphism group\nof $X$ acts transitively on the set of vertices of $X$. If the face-cycles at\nall the vertices in a map are of same type then the map is called\nsemi-equivelar. In general, semi-equivelar maps on a surface form a bigger\nclass than vertex-transitive maps. There are semi-equivelar toroidal maps which\nare not vertex-transitive. In this article, we show that semi-equivelar\ntoroidal maps are quotients of vertex-transitive toroidal maps. More\nexplicitly, we prove that each semi-equivelar toroidal map has a finite\nvertex-transitive cover. In 2019, Drach {\\em et al.} have shown that each\nvertex-transitive toroidal map has a minimal almost regular cover. Therefore,\nsemi-equivelar toroidal maps are quotients of almost regular toroidal maps.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 21 Apr 2020 12:33:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-22"}
